observations.recommendation:
We recommended that Management:
Direct the Municipal Accountant to maintain a complete and updated set of SLCs for all types of items under the inventory account;
Instruct the Municipal Accountant to prepare JEV for the recognition of drugs and medicines on hand as of year-end amounting to ₱365,198.00;
Instruct the Municipal Accountant to course through the inventory account all procurement of drugs and medicines as well as other procurement of supplies and materials pursuant to the perpetual inventory method; and
Require the Supply Officer to properly classify all supplies and materials reported in the RPCI.

We recommended that Management require the Supply Officer to:
Implement a standardized physical filing system for all procurement and issuance documents, including RIS, to ensure that copies are readily accessible for audit and review with proper indexing, dating, and labeling;
Properly consolidate the RIS issued and prepare SSMI using the correct format, which shall serve as the basis of the Municipal Accountant in recording the issued supplies as expense;
Recreate the ICS, ensuring that it is issued in the name of the actual custodian or end-user of the item. Additionally, require each employee to acknowledge receipt of his assigned items to establish clear accountability and proper documentation;
Prepare and maintain physical copies of Stock Cards for transparency and easy access for audit; and
Prepare and submit a RPCI to the Audit Team within the reglementary period.

We recommended that Management:
Instruct the Municipal Accountant to:
Set-up RPT/SET Receiva-bles at the beginning of the year based on the Certified List of Taxpayers prepared by the Treasu-rer's Office;
Recognize in the books of accounts the reversal of the corres-ponding receivable and liability accounts being set up at the beginning of the year once taxes are earned/ collected;
Coordi-nate with the Acting-Municipal Treasurer to reconcile their records of RPT/SET Receiva-bles and thereafter, conduct regular reconcilia-tion to support the integrity of the accounts;
Prepare and maintain subsidiary ledgers or details of taxpayers to support the amount recorded in the books as RPT Receiva-bles; and
Require the Acting Municipal Treasurer to:
Furnish the Municipal Accountant a copy of the Certified List of Taxpayers at the beginning of the year as her basis in setting-up the RPT/SET Receivables.

We recommended that Management require the LSB to:
Submit to the Audit Team a copy of the three-year program indicating strategic prioritiza-tion policies in the allocation of the SEF to schools, if already prepared;
Gather and keep records of the informa-tion needed to be considered in the planning and budgeting for SEF, particular-ly the SIP and the DEDP;
Ensure that concerned officials and employees provide necessary, complete, accurate, and timely reports, data, and informa-tion for the prepara-tion of the SEF plan and budget; and
Allocate funds for the ECCD Program within the SEF Budget;
Instruct the PSDS or co-chairman of the MSB to:
Prepare the SEF Budget using the prescribed form, specifically identifying the PPAs to be implement-ted under the fund for proper monitoring and implementa-tion; and
Obtain an authoriza-tion from the MSB through a resolution prior to utilization of generic appropria-tions stated in the SEF budget to ensure transparen-cy and accounta-bility in the utilization of SEF.

We recommended that Management require the MENRO-Designate to coordinate with the Provincial GSO and DOST to conduct the training on WACS which is the only requirement left prior to the approval of the 10-year SWMP.  

We also recommended that Management require the Municipal Solid Waste Management Board to closely monitor the approval of the 10-year SWMP upon compliance with the last requirement and implement it accordingly upon approval.
We further recommended that Management: 
Require the MENRO-Designate to strictly enforce the mandatory use of the complete set of personal protective equipment to the personnel directly involved in handling wastes to avoid compromising their health and safety while performing their assigned duties;
Provide for the installation of separate compartments with cover in the garbage trucks for segregation of waste during collection and transport;
Place sufficient details for identification on the body of all motor vehicles used for the collection and transport of solid wastes;
Enforce the "No Segregation, No Collection" policy with strict compliance monitoring at the barangay level;
Instruct the Municipal Engineer to conduct technical assessment to determine the electrical requirement and address any infrastructure limitations for the immediate installation of the necessary electrical system to ensure the operationalization of the machines;
Direct the MENRO-Designate to organize capacity-building workshops to train LGU personnel and waste management workers on the proper operation, maintenance, and troubleshooting of the machines. Likewise, develop standard operating procedures for the use and maintenance of the machines to ensure efficient and long-term functionality; and
Require the MENRO-Designate to conduct routine inspections and preventive maintenance to keep the machines in optimal condition and store the equipment in a safe and protected area to prevent exposure to environmental factors that may cause premature wear and tear.

We recommended that Management:
Assign serial/control numbers to all driver’s trip tickets to be issued;
Orient and require the drivers to properly accomplish the trip tickets indicating all the necessary information for proper control and monitoring of fuel consumption;
Sign/approve trip tickets only when the actual name of passenger/s are indicated in the trip ticket to establish who actually used government-owned vehicles. Likewise, avoid indicating generic terms for the purpose of travel like “official business”, “emergency”, and “government transaction”, instead indicate the actual purpose of travel in detail;
Instruct all drivers to require their passengers to sign the trip tickets and assign personnel to monitor such procedure; and
Require the concerned personnel to prepare and submit to the Audit Team the Report of Fuel Consumption and require the drivers to prepare and submit the Monthly Report of Official Travels.

We recommended that Management direct the Acting Municipal Treasurer and BPLO-Designate to expedite the completion of the necessary requirements for the automation of business license, permit, and clearance applications and issuance thereof through the e-BOSS system.

We further recommended that Management instruct the Acting Municipal Treasurer and BPLO-Designate to:
Ensure the completeness of required documents submitted by applicants of business permits and ensure that all documents are properly signed;
Ensure that the ‘jurat’ section of the Sworn Statement of Capital Investment/Gross Sales form is completely and accurately filled-out before it is signed by the Local Chief Executive;
Allocate time to examine the books, accounts, and other pertinent records of any person, partnership and corporation or in case of any suspected-under-declaration of gross sales to accurately determine, assess, and collect the correct amount due; and
Require all business owners to submit a certified photocopy of their income tax returns on or before April 30 of each year and collect any tax deficiency, if any, including interest at the rate of two percent per month from January to May. Otherwise, enforce the corresponding penalty for non-compliance therewith.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive:
• Prepare an Office Order designating an Inspectorate Committee;
• Instruct the members to strictly observe the inspection of deliveries as to quantity and conformity to specifications based on the DR and approved PO/contract;
• Indicate notation, if any, on the AIR if deliveries are not in conformity to the specifications or incomplete;
• Instruct the Acting Municipal Treasurer to explain in writing the lack of AIR upon the acceptance of the mini dump truck from the supplier; and
• Require the concerned supplier to replace the equipment delivered with item that conforms to specifications laid out in the bid documents.

We recommended that Management require the BAC to:
• Update/Revise the RFQ form used in gathering the lowest calculated and responsive quotation for all transactions involving procurement undertaken through alternative methods to indicate the ABC and other terms and conditions of the contract;
• Ensure that the RFQs, as a formal letter from the agency, are signed by the BAC Chairman;
• Require the supplier indicate the brand of goods they are offering with other necessary information that may affect the final evaluation of the offers;
• Prepare Abstract of Quotations after receiving and evaluating the price quotations received by them; and
• Prepare BAC Resolutions Recommending to the HOPE the Award of Contract in favor of the supplier with the Lowest Calculated and Responsive Quotation.

We recommended that Management:
• Instruct the Municipal Budget Officer and BAC to ensure that only those goods and services included in the APP and indicative APP be undertaken by the LGU;
• Require all department heads to properly and comprehensively plan their procurement activities, and to include in their PPMPs all items needed by their office or planned programs, projects and activities for the succeeding budget year to avoid or minimize the revisions thereof;
• Submit the same to the Municipal Budget Officer and BAC Secretariat for consolidation and evaluation; and
• Instruct the BAC to consolidate revised PPMPs into an updated or supplemental APP before proceeding with the procurement process.

We recommended that Management:
a. Require the Municipal Accountant and the GSO to adhere to the general process in handling and accounting for Inventories and Supplies and Materials prescribed in Section 122 of MNGAS in order to strengthen the internal control of the LGU;
b. Instruct the GSO to purchase supplies and materials needed for the quarter based on the approved annual procurement program, at the beginning of the year and of each subsequent quarters and through public bidding;
c. Direct the Municipal Accountant to use the Perpetual Inventory Method in the purchase of Supplies instead of recording as an outright expense in the books of accounts;
d. Instruct the Municipal Accountant and GSO to maintain stock/property cards and record deliveries and issuances therein; and
e. Require the GSO to regularly prepare the Summary of Supplies and Materials Issued (SSMI) and forward to Accounting Unit to serve as basis in the preparation of JEV and recording of issuance of supplies and materials.

We recommended that Management:
a.	Instruct the Inventory Committee to regularly conduct an Annual Physical Inventory and reconcile the same with accounting records to determine any discrepancy;
b.	Require the Municipal Treasurer and the Municipal Accountant to maintain Property Cards and Property, Plant and Equipment Ledger Cards (PPELC), respectively;
c.	Adhere to the general process in handling and accounting for PPE prescribed in Manual on the New Government Accounting System in order to strengthen the internal control of the agency; and
d.	Consider designating a General Services Officer (GSO) or Property Officer other than the Municipal Treasurer who shall perform functions pertaining to supply and property management of the Municipality.

